SIMPLE: attrition
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Attrition
<hw>At*tri"tion</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>attritio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>attrition</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of rubbing together; friction; the act of wearing by
friction, or by rubbing substances together; abrasion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Effected by <qex>attrition</qex> of the inward stomach.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being worn.</def>
<rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <def>Grief for sin arising only from
fear of punishment or feelings of shame. See <er>Contrition</er>.</def>
<rj><au>Wallis.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>attritional</ent>⟦br⟧
